725726f-b.text:
4th Street, west side, about 450 feet, north of Twentythird Avenue, showing four views of the Abraham Rapelye farmhouse and outhildiigs. This house was probably erected by Capt. Thoras Hagard shortly after 1724. This farm and the buildings were ovned and occupied bv members of the Rapelye familv from 1787 to 1896. The history of this area is that Thomas Stevenson had a patent in 1651 on the Rev. Francis Doughtv farm vhich lay between the Old Bowerv Road and Flushing Bay and south of Mill Creek or as it is also known as Jackson Greek. In 1787 it became the property of Abraham Rapelye. He built a dock on Flushing Bav just south of the mouth of Jacksonk Creek which in thos davs Was probably at 96t Street, and s outh of this house between Old Bowery Bay Rd. and the Hazard tract which was also purchased by Daniel Rapelve. It was later known as Strongs farm; it being the property of Aletta Rapelve Strong. The successive owners that followed Nere Wm. W. Thomas, Dr. Oliver Jones of Cold Spring Harbor,ard the Navahoe Realty Company. The Doughty house stood on the shore of Flushing Bay on a lare made by Dr. Adrian Van der Douck. IIt was the house of tNe Rapelye, Remsen and Strong farilies and was located at or near the present site of the Strong residence. The wing of the Ranelye house collapsed in November 1933 and the
buildinm was demolished in March 1934.

94th Street, west side, ahout 450 ft. north of Twentythird Avenue, shoxing four views of the Ahraham Rapelye house of 1852. These views are taken looking south from Ditmars Boulevard. This section of 94th Street is the original Old Bowery Road. Simon Remsen (b. 1748) married a daughter of Daniel Rapelye and occupied this farm. His daumhter married James Strong whose heirs owned it ir 1881. See other views for
